<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870219-0099 </DOCNO><HL> Four Boeing PlanesOrdered by British Air</HL><DD> 02/19/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> BA BABAIRLINES (AIR)AEROSPACE (ARO) </IN><DATELINE> SEATTLE  </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Boeing Commercial Airplane Co. unit of Boeing Co. said British Airways ordered three 757 jetliners and a 747-200 jumbo jet for a total of about $230 million.    The wide-bodied 747, a so-called Combi aircraft designed to carry a large freight load as well as passengers, will be the 53rd 747 in the London-based airline's fleet. British Airways now has on order 28 of the twin-engine, 180-seat 757s.    Boeing said all four aircraft will be powered by Rolls-Royce Ltd. RB211 engines. The 757s and 747 are scheduled to be delivered in the spring of 1988, Boeing said. </TEXT></DOC>